# AI Test Verification Standard

**AI-written tests aren't trusted by default.**

Every test scenario generated by AI must pass all five verification gates before it is considered complete. This applies regardless of which model, pipeline, or tool produced the test.

## Verification Gates

### 1. Positive scenarios pass
The feature works as the .feature file says. Run the scenario against the live application and confirm it passes green.

### 2. Negative scenarios pass
Failure modes are correctly rejected. Edge cases and boundary conditions are exercised and the system responds as expected.

### 3. Mutation verification
If we break the product, the tests catch it. Introduce a deliberate defect — remove a guard, flip a condition, comment out a save — and verify the scenario turns red. A test that does not catch a regression is a paper tiger.

### 4. Assertion cross-reference
What the test checks matches what the scenario claims to verify. Read the Gherkin `Then` steps alongside the automation assertions side by side — they must align. No phantom assertions; no mismatch between description and code.

### 5. Selector / contract quality
Locators and contracts are stable and semantic. No DOM-path or generated-ID fragility. Selectors must come from the POM layer, never hardcoded XPaths or auto-generated IDs.

## Delivery Standard

> Every test ships with a video, a mutation report, and an audit. No artefacts → not done.

| Artefact | What it proves |
|---|---|
| **Video** | Trace or recording of the passing run |
| **Mutation report** | Evidence that a deliberate break was caught |
| **Audit** | Assertion cross-reference confirmed — description matches code |

A test is only complete when all five gates are verified and all three artefacts exist.
